This paper is about dialogue act recognition, which is a subfield of natural language processing (NLP). The use of recurrent neural networks (RNNs) and conditional random fields (CRFs) is common in NLP, which suggests that this paper is likely to be in the cs.CL (Computation and Language) category. Additionally, the use of deep learning techniques such as hierarchical RNNs and bidirectional LSTMs suggests that this paper could also be in the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) category. The paper also focuses on improving performance on benchmark datasets, which suggests that it could be in the cs.LG (Machine Learning) category. The use of CRFs to model dependencies between labels and utterances suggests that this paper could also be in the cs.SD (Sound) category, which includes speech recognition and processing. Finally, the use of multiple levels of representation and the focus on improving accuracy despite noisy data suggests that this paper could also be in the cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) category, which includes research on neural networks and their applications.
